South Korea's central epidemic prevention department has said it will further expand the scope of new coronavirus detection. In addition, the de-quarantining criteria for contacts of confirmed cases have also been raised following isolation. The Central Clinical Committee of New Infectious Diseases in South Korea warned at a press conference on the 20th that cases of advanced age or underlying diseases may appear clinically severe. The committee speculates that viral replication is active during the initial infection phase of new crown cases, and that community transmission may occur in asymptomatic or mild patients before diagnosis.

The committee has called on the government to proceed with the development of new coronaviruses and therapeutic drugs, and has said that the current outbreak is likely to shift to the phase of community transmission, requiring a restructuring of the administrative, preventive and health systems and the maximum effective use of public health resources.

The health and well-being committee of the Korean National Assembly held a plenary session on the 20th and voted to pass three bills aimed at responding to the epidemic, including amendments to the law on Prevention and management of Infectious Diseases, the quarantine law and the medical law. The amendments, which have been approved by the Commission on the rule of law and justice, will be submitted to a plenary session of the National Assembly within months at the earliest.

According to the amendment to the law on the prevention and management of infectious diseases, if the level of early warning of infectious diseases is higher than "Note" , the government will provide materials such as masks for vulnerable groups, and the export of face masks and hand sanitizers may be prohibited for a specified period, medical personnel and pharmacists will be obliged to confirm the patient's overseas travel history when prescribing and dispensing drugs.

Under the amendment to the Quarantine Act, the Minister of Health and Welfare may request the Minister of Justice to prohibit the entry of foreigners from an epidemic or epidemic-risk area. The amendment to the medical law stipulates that medical institutions will build new infectious disease monitoring systems to strengthen the prevention and control of patients, guardians and medical personnel.
